# Enumerator.elm ŌĆö INTRICATE, the BFS move generator

The Elm port of Python's `bfs_solver._enumerate_moves`. Given
a `Buckets` state, returns every legal next move + the
post-state. Each move corresponds to one DSL line in the BFS
plan.

## Status

- **Label:** WORKHORSE + INTRICATE.
- **Mirrors:** `python/bfs_solver.py` lines ~155ŌĆō470
  (`_enumerate_moves` and the 5 move-type loops).
- **Divergences:** Python yields a generator; Elm returns a
  `List (Move, Buckets)`. Python's helper functions stay
  module-private; Elm's mirror them with the same names
  (without leading underscore).

## The five move types (must touch a trouble card)

- `(a)` **Absorb a neighbor into TROUBLE/GROWING.**
  - Source = HELPER stack via extract verb (peel / pluck /
    yank / steal / split_out). Emits `ExtractAbsorb`. The
    five extract verbs together cover every card on every
    helper ŌĆö `SplitOut` (added 2026-04-26) closes the
    interior-of-length-3-run gap that left earlier ports
    unable to extract certain interior cards.
  - Source = TROUBLE singleton (free pull). Emits `FreePull`.
- `(b)` **Push a TROUBLE 1- or 2-partial onto a HELPER**
  stack so the helper grows. Emits `Push`.
- `(b')` **Engulf**: a GROWING 2-partial swallows a HELPER
  stack into one legal stack that graduates to COMPLETE.
  Same `Push` shape as (b); the bucket route is implicit.
- `(c)` **Splice**: insert a TROUBLE singleton into a HELPER
  pure/rb run, splitting it cleanly. Emits `Splice`.
- `(d)` **Shift**: peel a HELPER donor card to replace the
  stolen end of a length-3 run; no spawn. Emits `Shift`.

## Doomed-third filtering (OPTIMIZE_PYTHON, ported 2026-04-26)

Two complementary filters keep the BFS from chasing futile
partials:

- `completionInventory state` ŌĆö `Set ShapeKey` of
  `(value, suit)` shapes available as candidate "third
  cards": every helper card + every trouble singleton.
  Excludes growing/complete (sealed) and trouble 2-partials
  (committed).
- `completionShapes partial` ŌĆö shapes that would extend a
  length-2 partial into a legal length-3 stack.
- `hasDoomedThird partial inventory` ŌĆö true iff no
  completion candidate exists.
- `admissiblePartial merged inventory` ŌĆö combined gate:
  partial-OK + (if length-2) not-doomed. Used at every
  absorb call site (extract_absorb, free_pull, shift).

**Filter 1 (merge time):** every length-2 absorb result
goes through `admissiblePartial`. Skips moves that produce
dead-end partials.

**Filter 2 (state level, top of `enumerateMoves`):** if any
existing growing 2-partial has no completion candidate in
this state's inventory, the function short-circuits to
`[]`. Catches partials whose candidates were consumed
elsewhere mid-search.

The `inventory` set is computed once per state and threaded
through to every absorb-emit site.

## Loop inversion via `extractableIndex` (OPTIMIZE_PYTHON, ported 2026-04-26)

Python's pre-2026-04-25 absorb loop scanned every helper ├Ś
position and filtered by neighbor-shape match. The
inversion replaces that with `_extractable_index : helper
-> Map (value, suit) [(hi, ci, verb)]` built once per
state. The absorb loop then iterates over each absorber's
neighbor shapes and looks up matching helper positions
directly. `classify` runs once per helper (not per helper ├Ś
absorber); `verbFor` runs once per (helper ├Ś ci).

Elm port: `extractableIndex : List Stack -> Dict ShapeKey
(List ExtractEntry)` built at the top of `enumerateMoves`,
threaded alongside `inventory` through the absorb sites.
Shift's donor lookup also reads the index (filtered to
`verb == Peel`) instead of building a separate
`peelableCards` list, mirroring Python's 2026-04-26
consolidation.

## Pure-FP discipline

Every helper takes state, returns state. Lists treated as
immutable values (no mutation by convention). Mirrors the
2026-04-25 Python pass: `withoutAt`, `removeAbsorber`,
`graduate`, `extractPieces` are all pure.

## Pointers

- Python source: `python/bfs_solver.py` `_enumerate_moves`.
- DSL contract: `conformance/scenarios/planner.dsl`. Each
  scenario asserts at least one move of a named type fires.
  Currently exercised by Python; this Elm port flips the
  Elm stubs (`Expect.pass`) to live assertions.
- Tests: `tests/Game/Agent/EnumeratorTest.elm`.
